        <section>
            <title>Quick Guide</title>
            <para>To keep it simple and stupid, &HZproductname; dose not include some complicated
                    <glossterm>GIS</glossterm> functions but the transformation from raster
                    <glossterm>DEM</glossterm> data. The common procedure of file transformation is
                as follows:</para>
            <procedure>
                <title>Transform a File to <productname>EMCUBE</productname> Terrain Format</title>
                <step>
                    <para>Select the input file by click the button on the right side of the input
                        field, the file path can also be manually typed in.</para>
                    <note>
                        <para>After the proper input file is selected, a brief description of this
                            file is displayed literally in the metainfo filed. The description gives
                            some information that maybe helpful in setting parameters of
                            transformation. See the detailed explanation in <xref
                                linkend="sec-MetaInfo"/>.</para>
                    </note>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <para>Select the output file by click the button on the right side of the output
                        field, the file path can also be manually typed in.</para>
                    <note>
                        <para>The output file format is <productname>EMCUBE</productname> Terrain
                            Format which has a <filename>.trn</filename> extension.</para>
                    </note>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <para>In the local coordinate origin setting area, input the longitude, latitude
                        and height for the local coordinate origin. </para>
                    <note>
                        <para>The longitude and latitude are in <ulink
                                url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System"
                                >WGS84</ulink>
                            <ulink url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geographic_coordinate_system"
                                >geographic coordinate system</ulink>. Both accept decimal formats
                            or <glossterm linkend="gloss-DMS"><acronym>DMS</acronym></glossterm>
                            formats. See <xref linkend="sec-DecDMS"/> for the details. The height of
                            the origin is also based on <ulink
                                url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System"
                                >WGS84</ulink> vertical coordinate.</para>
                    </note>
                </step>
                <step performance="optional">
                    <para>Set the cut parameters if you want a chopped interested area. Input the
                        width and height of the target area in meters.</para>
                    <note>
                        <para>If not set, the whole image will be transformed. The cut shape is a
                            rectangular in the XY plane of local coordinate, which has width and
                            height as input with the center at the origin. For more information
                            about the local coordinate see <xref linkend="sec-LocCoor"/>.</para>
                    </note>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <para>Click <guibutton>Start</guibutton> button, the transforming process will
                        begin. Just wait awhile to get the results. The indicating message and
                        progress bar may give you some information about the process.</para>
                </step>
            </procedure>
            <para>The main screen is as follows:<informalfigure>
                    <screenshot>
                        <graphic fileref="resources/mainshot.png"/>
                    </screenshot>
                </informalfigure></para>
        </section>
